docs.abstract: Since 1900, the House and Senate have repeatedly failed to pass such a bill. Now the legislation could be on its way to the Oval Office.
docs.snippet: Since 1900, the House and Senate have repeatedly failed to pass such a bill. Now the legislation could be on its way to the Oval Office.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since at least 1900, members of the House and Senate have tried to pass a law making lynching a federal crime. The bills were consistently blocked, shelved or ignored, and the passage of time has rendered anti-lynching legislation increasingly symbolic.

headline.main: Congress Moves to Make Lynching a Federal Crime After 120 Years of Failure

docs.lead_paragraph: Welcome to Opinion’s commentary for Night 1 of the Republican National Convention. In this special feature, Times Opinion writers rank the evening on a scale of 1 to 10: 1 means the night was a disaster for Republicans; 10 means it could lead to a big polling bump for Trump-Pence. Here’s what our columnists and contributors thought of the event, which highlighted Kimberly Guilfoyle, Nikki Haley, Donald Trump Jr., Tim Scott and President Trump himself.

headline.main: Republican Convention: Best and Worst Moments From Night 1

docs.abstract: He — and his party — is much, much worse.
docs.snippet: He — and his party — is much, much worse.
docs.lead_paragraph: On May 4, 1970, the Ohio National Guard opened fire on student protesters, killing four. The 50th anniversary of the Kent State massacre passed with little notice in a nation preoccupied with Covid-19 — but now, suddenly, echoes of the Nixon era are everywhere. And Donald Trump seems to be deliberately invoking Nixon’s legacy, tweeting out “LAW & ORDER!” in the apparent hope that it will magically rescue his political fortunes.

headline.main: Donald Trump Is No Richard Nixon
headline.print_headline: Donald Trump Is No Richard Nixon

docs.abstract: “Between the World and Me,” Coates’s treatise on black male life in America, catapulted him to prominence. Coates spoke to The Times about his new book, “We Were Eight Years in Power,” his year in Paris and what he’s up to next.
docs.snippet: “Between the World and Me,” Coates’s treatise on black male life in America, catapulted him to prominence. Coates spoke to The Times about his new book, “We Were Eight Years in Power,” his year in Paris and what he’s up to next.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Ta-Nehisi Coates’s first book, “The Beautiful Struggle,” was published in 2008, it landed with barely a ripple. At the time, Mr. Coates was a struggling writer. He had lost three jobs, and he and his family relied on unemployment checks, his wife’s income and occasional support from his father to stay afloat. By the time the book came out in paperback, his fortune had shifted slightly; he’d become a regular contributor to The Atlantic magazine, writing a blog that attracted a moderate but engaged audience.

headline.main: Ta-Nehisi Coates and the Making of a Public Intellectual
